"""
Claude full /init-verifiers command parity model.
"""

class InitVerifierCommandDescriptor:
    typeName: text
    name: text
    description: text
    contentLength: i64
    progressMessage: text
    source: text

    static fn new() -> InitVerifierCommandDescriptor:
        InitVerifierCommandDescriptor(typeName: "prompt", name: "init-verifiers", description: "Create verifier skill(s) for automated verification of code changes", contentLength: 0, progressMessage: "analyzing your project and creating verifier skills", source: "builtin")

class InitVerifierPromptPart:
    typeName: text
    textValue: text

    static fn text(textValue: text) -> InitVerifierPromptPart:
        InitVerifierPromptPart(typeName: "text", textValue: textValue)

fn initVerifiersCommand() -> InitVerifierCommandDescriptor:
    InitVerifierCommandDescriptor.new()

fn initVerifiersPrompt() -> text:
    """Use the TodoWrite tool to track your progress through this multi-step task.

## Goal

Create one or more verifier skills that can be used by the Verify agent to automatically verify code changes in this project or folder. You may create multiple verifiers if the project has different verification needs (e.g., both web UI and API endpoints).

Do NOT create verifiers for unit tests or typechecking. Those are already handled by the standard build/test workflow and don't need dedicated verifier skills. Focus on functional verification: web UI (Playwright), CLI (Tmux), and API (HTTP) verifiers.

## Phase 1: Auto-Detection

Analyze the project to detect what's in different subdirectories. The project may contain multiple sub-projects or areas that need different verification approaches.

1. Scan top-level directories to identify distinct project areas:
   - Look for separate package.json, Cargo.toml, pyproject.toml, go.mod in subdirectories
   - Identify distinct application types in different folders

2. For each area, detect:
   - Project type and stack
   - Primary languages and frameworks
   - Package managers
   - Web app, CLI tool, or API service
   - Existing verification tools
   - Dev server configuration

3. Installed verification packages for web apps:
   - Check if Playwright is installed
   - Check MCP configuration for Playwright MCP, Chrome DevTools MCP, and Claude Chrome Extension MCP
   - For Python projects, check for playwright and pytest-playwright

## Phase 2: Verification Tool Setup

Based on what was detected in Phase 1, help the user set up appropriate verification tools.

### For Web Applications

If browser automation tools are already installed or configured, ask the user which one they want to use. If none are detected, ask whether they want to install or configure Playwright, Chrome DevTools MCP, Claude Chrome Extension, or none.

If user chooses Playwright, run the package-manager-specific install command. If user chooses Chrome DevTools MCP or Claude Chrome Extension, configure MCP server settings as requested.

### For CLI Tools

Check if asciinema is available. If not available, inform the user that asciinema can help record verification sessions but is optional. Tmux is typically system-installed, just verify it is available.

### For API Services

Check if HTTP testing tools are available: curl and httpie. No installation is typically needed.

## Phase 3: Interactive Q&A

Based on the areas detected in Phase 1, you may need to create multiple verifiers. For each distinct area, use AskUserQuestion to confirm verifier name and project-specific questions.

For web apps, ask for dev server command, dev server URL, and ready signal. For CLI tools, ask for entry point command and whether to record with asciinema. For APIs, ask for API server command and base URL.

Ask whether authentication is required. If login is required, ask for login method, test credentials as environment variables, and post-login indicator.

## Phase 4: Generate Verifier Skill

All verifier skills are created in the project root's .claude/skills/ directory. This ensures they are automatically loaded when Claude runs in the project.

Write the skill file to .claude/skills/<verifier-name>/SKILL.md.

Skill template structure:

```
---
name: <verifier-name>
description: <description based on type>
allowed-tools:
---

# <Verifier Title>

You are a verification executor. You receive a verification plan and execute it EXACTLY as written.

## Project Context
<Project-specific details from detection>

## Setup Instructions
<How to start any required services>

## Authentication
<If auth is required, include step-by-step login instructions here>

## Reporting

Report PASS or FAIL for each step using the format specified in the verification plan.

## Cleanup

After verification:
1. Stop any dev servers started
2. Close any browser sessions
3. Report final summary

## Self-Update

If verification fails because this skill's instructions are outdated, or if the user corrects you mid-run, use AskUserQuestion to confirm and then Edit this SKILL.md with a minimal targeted fix.
```

Allowed tools by type:

verifier-playwright:
- Bash(npm:*)
- Bash(yarn:*)
- Bash(pnpm:*)
- Bash(bun:*)
- mcp__playwright__*
- Read
- Glob
- Grep

verifier-cli:
- Tmux
- Bash(asciinema:*)
- Read
- Glob
- Grep

verifier-api:
- Bash(curl:*)
- Bash(http:*)
- Bash(npm:*)
- Bash(yarn:*)
- Read
- Glob
- Grep

## Phase 5: Confirm Creation

After writing the skill file(s), inform the user where each skill was created, how the Verify agent discovers them, that they can edit the skills, that they can run /init-verifiers again, and that the verifier will offer to self-update if its instructions are outdated."""

fn getPromptForInitVerifiersCommand() -> [InitVerifierPromptPart]:
    [InitVerifierPromptPart.text(initVerifiersPrompt())]

fn initVerifiersSourceLinesModeled() -> i64:
    262

